You can achieve this by adding an event listener for the keydown event and checking if the Escape key was pressed. Then, check if the modal-overlay div is visible, and either show a close button or close the modal.

Implementation

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Modal with Escape Key</title>
  <style>
    .modal-overlay {
      display: none;
      position: fixed;
      top: 0;
      left: 0;
      width: 100%;
      height: 100%;
      background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
      z-index: 9999;
    }
    .modal {
      position: absolute;
      top: 50%;
      left: 50%;
      transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
      background: white;
      padding: 20px;
      border-radius: 5px;
      text-align: center;
    }
    .close-button {
      position: absolute;
      top: 10px;
      right: 10px;
      background: red;
      color: white;
      border: none;
      border-radius: 3px;
      padding: 5px;
      cursor: pointer;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <!-- Modal -->
  <div class="modal-overlay" id="modalOverlay">
    <div class="modal">
      <button class="close-button" id="closeButton">X</button>
      <p>This is a modal. Press Escape to close.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <button id="showModal">Show Modal</button>

  <script>
    const modalOverlay = document.getElementById('modalOverlay');
    const closeButton = document.getElementById('closeButton');
    const showModal = document.getElementById('showModal');

    // Show modal function
    showModal.addEventListener('click', () => {
      modalOverlay.style.display = 'block';
    });

    // Close modal function
    const closeModal = () => {
      modalOverlay.style.display = 'none';
    };

    closeButton.addEventListener('click', closeModal);

    // Close modal on Escape key press
    document.addEventListener('keydown', (event) => {
      if (event.key === 'Escape' && modalOverlay.style.display === 'block') {
        closeModal();
      }
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>

Explanation

1. HTML Structure:

modal-overlay: The background overlay for the modal.

modal: The modal content box.

close-button: A button to manually close the modal.



2. CSS:

The modal is initially hidden using display: none.

The modal and overlay are styled for a centered



